On Wednesday, February 19, 2003, at 01:19PM, Robert S. Williams, MD <rwill(-at-)arkansas.net> wrote:

>I'm told Oil starts to lubricate best at around 200 degrees. I would be
>cautious about running at over 280 degrees.... the thing is, a great deal
>depends on the ambient outdoor temp....if it's hot, expect to run hotter oil
>temps... for the winter, you want around 200 degrees for best engine
>lubrication. See the discussion on the "Hoover Sermons" webpage.

The oil chemistry and engine cooling design is pretty complicated. However, I've read that you have to hit at least 180F if you expect the engine to last. Between 180-200F the contaminants in the oil begin to burn off. Water/condensation boils at 212F...

